feat: migrate from Teams to Zoom meeting integration

- Add ZoomMeetingService to replace TeamsMeetingService
- Add ZoomTokenProvider for Server-to-Server OAuth authentication
- Update MeetingResponse DTO to handle Zoom API response format
- Replace Microsoft Graph API calls with Zoom API endpoints
- Support meeting CRUD operations (create, update, cancel)
- Remove dependency on per-user Microsoft tokens
- Fix organizational account authentication issues

Breaking changes:
- Replace teams_meeting_id/teams_join_url with zoom_meeting_id/zoom_join_url
- Remove GraphUserTokenProvider dependency

feat: Add comprehensive task management system with AWS S3 integration and user hierarchy

Task Management System:
- Added TaskController, TaskService, and TaskRepository with complete CRUD operations
- Implemented task status workflow (IN_PROGRESS → PENDING_REVIEW → COMPLETED) with role-based transitions
- Created DTOs for task operations (CreateTaskRequest, UpdateTaskRequest, UpdateTaskStatusRequest, TaskResponse)
- Added task assignment functionality with organizational hierarchy validation

Comment System:
- Added CommentController, CommentService, and CommentRepository for task collaboration with complete CRUD operations
- Created DTOs for comment operations (CreateCommentRequest, CommentResponse)

Document Management & AWS S3:
- Integrated AWS S3 for file storage with S3Service, S3Config, and AWS SDK dependencies
- Added DocumentController, DocumentService, and DocumentRepository for file operations
- Created DTOs for document operations (UploadDocumentRequest, DocumentResponse, DocumentDownloadResponse)
- Implemented secure file upload with unique S3 key generation and metadata storage
- Added presigned URL generation for secure direct downloads from S3 (15-minute expiration)
- Implemented proper file cleanup with S3 deletion on document removal

Data Models & Database:
- Created core entities (Task, TaskComment, TaskDocument) with proper JPA relationships
- Added enums for Priority (LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH) and TaskStatus workflow states

User Management & Hierarchy:
- Added UserController with /users/assignable endpoint for organizational hierarchy
- Integrated HierarchyService to get users below current user in organizational structure
- Created AssignableUser DTO for clean user selection in task assignment

This commit establishes the complete backend foundation for task management, file handling, and collaborative features with production-ready AWS integration and efficient data access patterns.

feat: Add comprehensive proposal management system with cross-committee collaboration and generic services

Proposal Management System:
- Added ProposalController, ProposalService, and ProposalRepository with complete CRUD operations using committee/subcommittee entities
- Implemented proposal status workflow (IN_PROGRESS → PENDING_REVIEW → COMPLETED) with role-based transitions and automatic cross-committee request status synchronization
- Created DTOs for proposal operations (CreateProposalRequest, UpdateProposalRequest, UpdateProposalStatusRequest, ProposalResponse) with committee-based assignment structure
- Added committee and subcommittee repository

Cross-Committee Request System:
- Added cross-committee request functionality within ProposalController and ProposalService for inter-committee collaboration
- Implemented cross-committee request creation, retrieval, and status management
- Created DTOs for cross-committee operations (CreateCrossCommitteeRequestRequest, CrossCommitteeRequestResponse, UpdateCrossCommitteeRequestStatusRequest)

Generic Comment & Document Services:
- Refactored CommentService and DocumentService to support multiple entity types (TASK, PROPOSAL, CROSS_COMMITTEE_REQUEST) through EntityType enum
- Implemented generic comment/document operations that work across tasks, proposals, and cross-committee requests with unified API endpoints

Data Models & Database Schema:
- Created entities (Proposal, ProposalComment, ProposalDocument, CrossCommitteeRequest, CrossCommitteeRequestComment, CrossCommitteeRequestDocument) with proper JPA relationships
- Added ProposalStatus and CrossCommitteeRequestStatus enums

This commit establishes the complete backend foundation for proposal management with cross-committee collaboration, generic service architecture, and committee-based organizational workflows.

feat(meetings): add recurring meeting support and series updates

- Added recurrenceId and recurrenceRule handling in Meeting model and DTOs
- Extended MeetingController and MeetingService to update single occurrence vs entire series
- Updated repository and hierarchy service logic for recurrence
- Improved exception handling with ZoomSyncException and MeetingNotFoundException
- Adjusted application.properties configs for recurrence handling
- Added MeetingServiceTest coverage for recurring meetings

feat(notes,performance): add meeting notes and performance tracking

- Implemented MeetingNote entity, repository, and service for user notes on meetings
- Added MeetingNoteController with endpoints to add/update/delete notes
- Introduced MeetingEvaluation flow:
  • DTOs for requests/responses
  • Service and repository to persist evaluations
  • Controller endpoints for performance updates
- Supports updating performance metrics at meeting level
- Extended tests and DTOs for consistent API responses

feat(progress): add progress search, history, and visibility services

- Added ProgressSearchController to query user/meeting progress
- Implemented HistoryController + HistoryService for performance history tracking
- Introduced VisibilityService to control access to progress data
- Added lightweight DTOs (UserCardDto, ParticipantLiteDto) for efficient API responses
- Updated User model with fields required for visibility/progress
- Secured endpoints with MeetingGuard for role/permission checks

issue.body:
### Description
Our `orderController.js` currently supports:
- Placing an order (`placeOrder`)
- Fetching orders (`getOrders`)

However, there’s **no way to cancel an order** once placed.  
We need to add an API endpoint that allows a logged-in user to cancel their order before it’s processed or delivered.

---

### Proposed Solution
- **Controller**: Add a new function `cancelOrder` in `orderController.js`.
- **Flow**:
  1. Accept `orderId` from request params.
  2. Verify that the order belongs to `req.user._id`.
  3. Allow cancellation **only if** order status is `"pending"` or `"processing"`.
  4. Update order’s status to `"cancelled"` and save changes.
  5. Return updated order details in response.

---

### Acceptance Criteria
- ✅ User can cancel only their own orders.
- ✅ Orders with status `"delivered"` or `"shipped"` cannot be cancelled.
- ✅ Returns proper success/error messages.
- ✅ Proper error handling if order not found.

pull_request.title: feat: Implement comprehensive modeling framework with GUI
pull_request.body:
This commit delivers a complete, feature-rich hydraulic and hydrological modeling framework, built in response to user requests for a Preissmann-based model and a rapid modeling tool.

The project was developed in three main stages:

1.  **1D Hydraulic Model (`preissmann_model`)**:
    - A stable and verified model that solves the Saint-Venant equations using the implicit Preissmann scheme.
    - Includes support for hydraulic structures like `Gate` and `Pump` as internal boundary conditions.

2.  **Coupled Modeling Framework (`common` package)**:
    - A `BaseModelComponent` interface and `SimulationController` allow for connecting different model types (e.g., hydrological and hydraulic) into a single simulation.
    - Supports network topologies, including converging and diverging branches via a `Junction` component. This framework can handle any directed acyclic graph of model components.

3.  **Rapid Modeling GUI & Interface**:
    - A GUI built with the `eel` library for visually building model networks by dragging and dropping components, editing their properties, and defining connections.
    - A YAML configuration file format for defining models and networks without code.
    - A `ConfigParser` that reads the YAML file and automatically builds the simulation.
    - A generic `run_from_config.py` script to execute models directly from the configuration file.
    - The GUI provides real-time feedback during simulations, including a live log and a live plot of results. It also allows for post-simulation analysis and plotting.

The project is fully documented with a GUI manual and a comprehensive case study to demonstrate its capabilities.
